{
  "text": "Our study showed a 1.1 \u00b5m decline in mean total RNFL thickness per decade of aging. This low decline may be due to the fact that significant age-related decay of the optic nerves occurs after the age of 60 years, [CITATION_1] and there were only six subjects who were 60 years and older in our study. However, this association may not be uniform across the entire age spectrum and there might be some subtle associations when age is disaggregated into children and adults. The age-related decline in RNFL thickness should be taken into account when establishing normal limits, as it can be considerable in individual segments. For example, studies [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] have shown that the largest age-dependent decline in RNFL occur in the supero-temporal and infero-temporal quadrants, in which the main blood vessels are located, and could be responsible for the shape and thickness of the RNFL profile.",
  "citation_candidates": [
